<TITLE> Bangladesh set to chair ILO conference </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 28 (bdnews24.com)Bangladesh's labour minister is set to chair the International Labour Conference for the first time, with the global job crisis topping the agenda of the meeting starting June 1 in Geneva, Switzerland. "This is the first time in the 36 years of its ILO membership Bangladesh has got the chance of presiding over the convention," labour secretary Ataharul Islam told reporters at the ministry on Thursday. Alongside labour minister Khandker Musharraf Hossain, the delegation will include state minister for labour and employment Munnuzan Sufian and 13 other members. "This will be a rare honour for Bangladesh as representatives from 182 countries will participate in the conference," said Islam. The conference from June 1-19 will focus on the global job crisis, global recession, labour rights, gender disparity and abolition of child labour, among other issues. "Besides, the Bangladesh delegation will focus on expansion of new labour markets and welfare of our expatriates," said the labour secretary. A special session on 'The Global Job Crisis', will be held on June 15-16 with the participation of heads of the state. Prime minister Sheikh Hasina is expected to address the session on June 15, said Islam. About seven million Bangladeshis work abroad in different countries of the world. b
